objects.name: APT1
objects.description: A single organization operating since at least 2006 that conducted long-running, large-scale cyber espionage against at least 141 organizations across 20 industries, primarily English-speaking. APT1 leveraged aggressive spear phishing, custom and public malware (notably the WEBC2 beachhead and BISCUIT standard backdoor), email-stealing utilities (GETMAIL, MAPIGET), and maintained persistence (average 356 days; up to 1,764 days). It stole hundreds of terabytes of data and used an extensive hop infrastructure and Chinese (Simplified) systems in Shanghai (primarily China Unicom/China Telecom netblocks), frequently proxying via HTRAN. Mandiant assesses APT1 is likely PLA Unit 61398, with training in computer security and English, operating from the Pudong New Area of Shanghai.
aliases: PLA General Staff Department 3rd Department 2nd Bureau

objects.name: UglyGorilla
objects.description: APT1 persona active since at least 2004. Registered APT1 infrastructure (e.g., hugesoft.org), authored malware (e.g., MANITSME) and left identifiable signatures (e.g., 'No Doubt to Hack You, Writed by UglyGorilla'). Used Shanghai-based IPs and the email uglygorilla@163.com; associated with domains and WEBC2-UGX protocol usage. Publicly showed interest in China’s 'cyber troops' and used 'rouji' (meat-chicken) hacker slang.

objects.name: DOTA
objects.description: APT1 persona operating multiple sequential webmail accounts for spear phishing and social engineering (e.g., Hotmail/Gmail), sometimes registering accounts from APT1 hop infrastructure and using a Shanghai mobile number (159-2193-7229) for SMS verification. Communicated fluently in English to targets (e.g., SE Asian military orgs). Frequently used pattern-based passwords (e.g., '1qaz@WSX#EDC') and the shorthand '2j3c1k' suggestive of PLA organizational structure.

objects.name: SuperHard
objects.description: APT1 malware developer persona, creator or key contributor to AURIGA and BANGAT families, including kernel-mode components. Signed work via PE version info, and modified binaries (e.g., 'superhard corp.'). Rootkit.com account registered from APT1 egress range; online traces place him in/near Shanghai’s Pudong New Area.

objects.name: People’s Liberation Army Unit 61398
objects.description: The 2nd Bureau of the PLA General Staff Department’s 3rd Department (SIGINT/CNO), assessed to be APT1. Based in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai, with a 12-story center building at 208 Datong Road. Staffed by hundreds to thousands, recruits with English and technical skills, and received special fiber infrastructure via China Telecom in the name of national defense.

objects.name: People’s Liberation Army (PLA)
objects.description: China’s military reporting to the Communist Party of China’s Central Military Commission. Assessed to house its strategic cyber command within the General Staff Department 3rd Department for SIGINT/CNO.

objects.name: PLA General Staff Department 3rd Department
objects.description: PLA department focused on SIGINT, foreign language proficiency, and defense information systems; includes the 2nd Bureau (Unit 61398) and is linked to APT1’s mission, capabilities, and resources.

objects.name: Communist Party of China (CPC)
objects.description: China’s ultimate authority; PLA reports to the CPC’s Central Military Commission. The report argues the CPC is aware of and tasking PLA cyber operations against foreign organizations.

objects.name: China Telecom
objects.description: State-influenced telecom that 'co-built' fiber optic communications for PLA Unit 61398 (per an internal memo), providing channel ports and infrastructure under national defense imperatives.

objects.name: China Unicom Shanghai Network
objects.description: Regional ISP owning major Shanghai netblocks (e.g., 223.166.0.0/15, 58.246.0.0/15, 112.64.0.0/15, 139.226.0.0/15) heavily used by APT1 for egress to hops and HTRAN C2 traffic.

objects.name: China Mobile
objects.description: Chinese mobile carrier; a Shanghai-allocated number (159-2193-7229) was used by the APT1 persona 'DOTA' to verify email registrations.

objects.name: webc2 (family)
objects.description: APT1’s beachhead backdoor family in use since at least 2004, designed to retrieve web pages and parse commands embedded between specific HTML tags (earlier variants used HTML comments). Variants (e.g., KT3, QBP, RAVE, ADSPACE, HEAD, DIV, TABLE, TOCK, UGX, YAHOO, Y21K, AUSOV, CLOVER, CSON, BOLID) typically support opening a shell, downloading/executing files, and sleeping. WEBC2 samples showed continuous iterative development with build paths and dates; commonly used as initial foothold from spear phishing.

objects.name: biscuit
objects.description: APT1 'standard backdoor' in use since at least 2007, supporting a wide range of commands (e.g., bdkzt for shell, file download/upload, process and service management, registry changes, system info, sleep). Provides robust remote control of victim systems beyond beachhead capabilities.

objects.name: getmail
objects.description: APT1 utility built to extract Microsoft Outlook PST contents, including messages, attachments, and folders. Supports date-bounded selection to periodically steal only recent emails.

objects.name: mapiget
objects.description: APT1 utility for extracting email that still resides on Microsoft Exchange servers using valid credentials, writing message bodies to text and saving attachments separately.

objects.name: manitsme
objects.description: APT1 backdoor family signed in code by 'UglyGorilla' (e.g., 'No Doubt to Hack You, Writed by UglyGorilla'). Provides remote control operations as part of APT1’s 'standard backdoors'.

objects.name: poison ivy
objects.description: Publicly available remote access Trojan occasionally used by APT1 as a backdoor to provide interactive control of victim systems.

objects.name: gh0st rat
objects.description: Public remote access Trojan occasionally used by APT1 to remotely control compromised systems with GUI and keylogging capabilities.

objects.name: macromail
objects.description: APT1 backdoor designed to mimic MSN Messenger traffic to blend with legitimate communications, supporting covert C2.

objects.name: glooxmail
objects.description: APT1 backdoor that mimics Jabber/XMPP traffic for covert communications with C2 servers.

objects.name: calendar
objects.description: APT1 backdoor that masquerades as Gmail Calendar traffic to hide C2 communications within seemingly legitimate protocol flows.

objects.name: auriga
objects.description: APT1 malware family linked to the 'SuperHard' persona; used by APT1 and other Chinese APT groups. Part of APT1’s standard post-compromise toolset.

objects.name: bangat
objects.description: APT1 malware family authored or significantly contributed to by 'SuperHard'; used by APT1 and other Chinese APT groups as part of remote access tooling.

objects.name: Analisi Malware: Webc2 (Family)
objects.description: This report contains technical analysis and indicators associated with malware. webc2 (family).
